title: For Sale:  Discontinued Marlin .44 Magnum 1894C
postcontent:
I bought this handsome monster in 1991 but it sat forlorn in various closets till last week, when I finally took it to the range to finally fire it. 20 rounds suggests this .44 magnum is just too much gun for me. And my bills were more than I'd expected so...

It has a cross-bar safety, a blued finish, the standard walnut stock, and a Micro-Groove barrel. (Wikipedia says "in the mid-1990s, Marlin changed the .357 and .44 barrels from 12-groove-or-more 'Micro-Groove' rifling to 6-groove 'Ballard' style rifling.") The only things wrong with this gun are that the folding leaf rear sight is broken off, and now there are a couple ugly but not fatal scratches on/near the sight from where I tried and failed to install a replacement (see photo). I figured out how to avoid scratching it again but not how to get the flimsy little plastic thing on without breaking it; then again the forums lead me to think a lot of folks buy yourselves niftier sights or install a scope anyway, so instead of going through that again I'm just asking less than I'd planned. (The rear leaf sight is available online for about $8 +S&H if you want that; I still have the little sight-raiser thing.)

Note that making some cash off this is important but I might accept a trade for an equivalent Marlin 1894 in a more manageable .357 magnum, a .45 ACP 1911 pistol, a .357 magnum revolver with a 4" barrel, or perhaps an SKS or AK-47 style rifle in good shape. A gun I haven't thought to list, or a partial-value trade with cash, is also worth suggesting. 

I'll want to draw up some document, and I won't be taking checks, credit cards, first-born sons, suckling goats, etc. And you'll need to show me your valid KY driver's license or state ID, and bring a photocopy for my records; if you want I'll reciprocate. A CCDW would also help by establishing you're legally allowed to own a gun (but that's optional; I don't have one yet). This will most likely be the only firearm I'll ever circulate, so I want to do it right.

title: For Sale:  Ishapore Lee Enfield  -  1943, CAI Imported - No. 1 Mk. III
postcontent:
Hello Armslist,

     The gun looks to be in 'Very Good' condition, the only rust I can see is some light surface rust on the front sight; a good steel wool scrubbing would see it disappear. Other than that, the gun is in 'Very Good' condition; I would say 80% of the bluing is still in place; I personally think the wear adds some charm to the rifle.

     The stock is pretty beat up, as one would expect of a military surplus rifle. It has been initialed on the stock 'C.F.'. There is also copper wiring wrapped around the rifle in two places. I am told by fellow collectors that these are attempts to strengthen the wood, as the rifle would be used to launch grenades, which had a brutal kick. So much so, that with normal bands, guns would shake themselves apart in a few weeks of combat without the added support of the wiring. This rifle in question even has an entire steel bolt under the rear wiring for this purpose, indicating that it was likely a grenadier's weapon. A tell-tale sign of this rifle's use in northern Africa is the 'pitch' or 'tar-grease' found in the nooks and crannies of the rifle; when soldiers ran out of traditional lubricants in the dry desert, they resorted to pilfering their vehicle's grease stores to keep the weapons firing.


     I'm in no hurry to sell this one. I haven't even had a chance to shoot it yet, but I will wait and see if someone else would like to have the first go. This is chambered in .303 British. It has been on my 'cleaning shelf' for a while now; I have worked on it on and off the past few weeks to clean it up. The barrel is almost perfect in terms of rifling, slight pitting near the receiver, but nothing to affect the performance of the rifle.

     This No. 1 is an awesome piece; early Enfields were some of the most accurate rifles built in the 20th century.


     Feel free to email me anytime with questions,


Regards,
     Thomas
